          <div id="hub-panel-briefs" class="hub-panel" data-hub-panel="briefs" role="tabpanel" hidden>
            <div class="text-center mb-8">
              <h3 class="section-title">Dream Research <span class="ethyria-gradient-text-emerald">Briefs</span></h3>
              <p class="section-subtitle">Concise science briefs on dream research, methods, and evidence.</p>
            </div>
            <div id="briefs-filter" class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 justify-center mb-8">
              <button data-brief-chip="all">All</button>
              <button data-brief-chip="core">Core Questions</button>
              <button data-brief-chip="method">Methods</button>
              <button data-brief-chip="database">Databases</button>
              <button data-brief-chip="evidence">Evidence</button>
            </div>
            <div id="briefs-grid" class="briefs-grid">
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="core">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--core">Core Question</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">Do all people dream?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Polysomnographic studies confirm that all healthy people dream, even though most dreams are not remembered.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>REM sleep occurs universally in all healthy individuals</li>
              <li>Dream recall varies widely between 10 and 90 percent</li>
              <li>People blind from birth dream non-visually but with emotional intensity</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Hobson 1988, Solms 1997, Jouvet 1967</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="core">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--core">Core Question</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What are dreams made of?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Dream content is neither random nor symbolically determined, but follows measurable cognitive and emotional patterns.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Around 80 percent of dreams contain familiar people and known settings</li>
              <li>Negative emotions outweigh positive ones across most cultures</li>
              <li>Sleep stage shapes dream character (REM vs. NREM)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Hall &amp; Van de Castle 1966, Domhoff 2003, Schredl 2010</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="core">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--core">Core Question</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--moderate">Moderate</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">Do dreams have a function?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Several hypotheses about dream function exist, but robust causal evidence for any single function remains limited.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>The emotion regulation hypothesis has moderate empirical support</li>
              <li>Memory consolidation during REM sleep is well established, the role of dream content is not</li>
              <li>The threat simulation theory remains scientifically controversial</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Walker &amp; van der Helm 2009, Revonsuo 2000, Hobson et al. 2000</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="core">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--core">Core Question</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--moderate">Moderate</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">Do dreams regulate emotion?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">REM sleep is linked to emotional processing, but the specific contribution of dream content is difficult to isolate.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>REM sleep deprivation measurably impairs emotional reactivity</li>
              <li>Emotional dreams occur more frequently after stressful days</li>
              <li>The causal link between dream content and emotion regulation remains unresolved</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Walker &amp; van der Helm 2009, Cartwright 2010, Scarpelli 2019</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="core">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--core">Core Question</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--limited">Limited</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">How reliable are dream reports?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Dream reports are retrospective and prone to memory distortion. Direct awakening studies yield more precise data.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Morning reports consistently underestimate actual dream frequency</li>
              <li>Immediate reports after targeted awakenings are significantly more accurate</li>
              <li>Social desirability measurably influences reported content</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Schredl 2002, Domhoff &amp; Schneider 1998, Baylor &amp; Cavallero 2001</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="method">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--method">Method</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What does Hall and Van de Castle content analysis measure?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">The Hall-Van de Castle system is the most widely used coding scheme in dream research with over 10,000 reports analyzed.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Codes characters, interactions, emotions, settings, and activities</li>
              <li>Norm samples from over 500 student dreams are publicly available</li>
              <li>Inter-rater reliability exceeds 0.85 under controlled conditions</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Hall &amp; Van de Castle 1966, Domhoff 2003, Schneider &amp; Domhoff 1995</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="method">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--method">Method</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">How does EEG work in dream research?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Polysomnography with EEG enables precise sleep stage classification and directly correlates brain activity with dream reports.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>REM sleep shows theta waves and activation of limbic structures</li>
              <li>NREM dreams are less vivid and less emotionally charged</li>
              <li>Awakening studies with EEG established foundational knowledge of dream physiology</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Hobson 1988, Siegel 2001, Stickgold 2005</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="method">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--method">Method</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--moderate">Moderate</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What can dream diaries contribute as a research method?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Dream diaries are the most common ecological method, but prone to selection bias and retrospective distortion.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Best results come from daily recording immediately after waking</li>
              <li>Long-term diaries over 90 days reveal stable individual patterns</li>
              <li>Digital capture improves data completeness and participant compliance</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Domhoff &amp; Schneider 1998, Schredl 2004, van de Castle 1994</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="method">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--method">Method</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--emerging">Emerging</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">How does automated dream content analysis work?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">NLP models can analyze dream reports for emotions, themes, and patterns, but validation against human coding remains challenging.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Word2Vec and BERT models achieve 70 to 80 percent agreement with human coding</li>
              <li>Emotion classification performs better than topic extraction</li>
              <li>Large datasets like DreamBank and SDDb enable initial longitudinal analyses</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Horikawa et al. 2017, Bulkeley 2018, Selterman et al. 2020</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="database">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--database">Database</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--emerging">Emerging</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What is the Sleep and Dream Database (SDDb)?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">The SDDb is one of the largest public collections of dream reports, with over 25,000 entries and an integrated search tool.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Contains reports from longitudinal studies, clinical contexts, and self-reports</li>
              <li>Searchable by content keywords, demographics, and sleep context</li>
              <li>Serves as the basis for computational linguistic analyses in dream research</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Bulkeley 2017, researchdata.edu.au</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="database">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--database">Database</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What is the International Journal of Dream Research?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">The IJoDR is the leading peer-reviewed open-access journal for empirical dream research, established in 2008.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>Covers dream content, emotions, recall, lucid dreaming, and clinical dream work</li>
              <li>Freely accessible via Heidelberg University</li>
              <li>Growing publication volume in a specialized field</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">IJoDR, journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="database">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--database">Database</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">Which dream databases exist?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Several specialized databases cover dream research, from clinical trials to large-scale self-report collections.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>DreamBank (UC Santa Cruz) contains over 22,000 reports with open access</li>
              <li>PubMed indexes over 8,000 peer-reviewed dream studies</li>
              <li>IASD connects dream researchers and clinicians worldwide</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">dreambank.net, PubMed, IASD</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="evidence">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--evidence">Evidence</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--high">High</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What do we know about emotions in dreams?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Dreams have a strongly negative emotional tone, which supports several theories of emotional regulation during sleep.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>70 to 80 percent of dream emotions are negative (fear, anger, sadness)</li>
              <li>Emotional intensity in dreams correlates with stressful daytime events</li>
              <li>Anxiety dreams and clinical nightmares have distinct etiologies</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Domhoff 2003, Hartmann 1995, Levin &amp; Nielsen 2007</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="evidence">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--evidence">Evidence</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--moderate">Moderate</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">How stable are recurring dream themes?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Recurring dreams show individual stability over years, but are culturally influenced and not universally shared.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>The most common themes are being chased, falling, exams, and flying</li>
              <li>Cultural differences appear primarily in specific symbols</li>
              <li>Recurring nightmares correlate with documented trauma exposure</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">Domhoff 1996, Nielsen et al. 2003, Yu 2012</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="brief-card" data-brief-category="evidence">
            <div class="brief-card-header">
              <span class="brief-badge brief-badge--evidence">Evidence</span>
              <span class="brief-evidence brief-evidence--moderate">Moderate</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="brief-card-title">What does research say about lucid dreaming?</h3>
            <p class="brief-card-summary">Lucid dreams are neurophysiologically measurable and can be trained, but their therapeutic efficacy is not yet robustly established.</p>
            <ul class="brief-card-findings">
              <li>EEG shows elevated gamma activity (40 Hz) during lucid phases</li>
              <li>The MILD technique doubles lucidity rates in laboratory settings</li>
              <li>Therapeutic use for nightmares shows initial positive results</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="brief-card-footer">
              <span class="brief-sources-label">LaBerge 1980, Stumbrys et al. 2012, Holzinger et al. 2015</span>
              <span class="brief-date">Jun 2026</span>
            </div>
          </div>
            </div>
          </div>
